Turkey Expands Its Diplomatic Horizons
Long before Turkey became a member of the European Union, the European powers had a desire to penetrate the interior of this country.
In the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps inland Asia, lies one of the most interesting relics of disastrous imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-Renaissance style.
At least, this is what the guides say.
The building is set to clock the end of the platforms and has in front of two towers, one for each corner, all resembling a typical German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The building in its complex is a bit decadent.
But once the vaulted door has been overcome, there is no doubt about the company’s greatness that this was the westernmost door.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a "late eater" in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railroad that ran to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during World War I.
Their railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Due to the relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, it fell below
British rule and when the forces advanced into Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German ally out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was also bad for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917 a munitions train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources said it was sabotage.
Since then, the station has been falling apart and left out of history.
But today, this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the eastern centres, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's willingness to expand its diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a new policy of collaboration.
The Turkish government has excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to evaluate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I went to the Turkish capital Ankara, in order to visit one of the leaders of the AKP, expert in foreign policy, the Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a trip of shakes, which produced the cadences of the ancient world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - new city, designed to rule a new secular state, far from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has raised some suspicions in the West, and especially in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure – built ad hoc – in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-sized shopping malls and “power bakeries” where middle-class managers in business suits – men and women – gather early in the morning to agree/do business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost any party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
“The party’s foreign policy objective is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off in relations with its interior.
Today you have to look both east and west at the same time.
This is not a case if it is not towards one or the other.
You have to do both.
"But surely at some point," I ask him, "could Turkey be forced to choose?"
“Turkey,” he replies, “doesn’t want to insult that choice.”
Then he underlines a point that almost everyone I have spoken to so far had recited to me almost from memory: the relations that Turkey has not only with the Middle East, but with the Caucasus region, and with the entire Black Sea, represent a benefit for Europe and the United States as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically mount those railway lines that open the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Again at Hydarpasha Station, after a second sleepless night, my thoughts return to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised would they have been to know that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East would, in large part, be in Turkey’s hands today?
And waiting at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe."
So there is not much doubt as to which continent this fascinating country should claim.
