The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization to the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support in total with 11.2 billion euros to this financial and insurance institution that also has business in Hungary.
This weekend, the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held high-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s head of economic competition.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer the crisis of the euro area in the context of the international financial crisis that is occurring in several waves more than a year ago, therefore the decisions taken with respect to the Bank, in a sense can be considered as precedent.
According to the decision taken in the early hours of Sunday, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a part of its business, including mainly the activities – mainly insurance – purchased last year from ABN Amr<0xC3><0xB3> in the Netherlands.
Fortis shares started a sharp decline last week and for the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees this Bank is too large to allow it to break down.
Shares of the company fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has decreased by more than two-thirds.
Looking at the current stock prices, the total value of the group’s capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management blamed the sharp drop in Fortis shares on the insecurities of the North American market in connection with the approval of the US $700 billion package plan.
On Monday, the shares showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new CEO.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has made a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had already assured investors that they had nothing to worry about, they are not going to lose their money.
There has been no panic among Bank customers so far, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when they see data from the drug purchase.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which to the use of the data of the recipes in all cases joins it to the approval of the given person.
The same should be in independent hands, because if not, "we entrust the chicken coop to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the prescription follow-up program.
Insurance companies make the price of insurance and the amount of compensation dependent on the client’s health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
They sent the client for medical check-up and signed the contract with him already knowing the result of the check-up.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the client’s diseases and health status.
For example, if you systematically take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a risk number, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has hardly anything to do, although there are minor difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multi-use, for example certain substances serve both to treat headaches and for heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk-increasing factor for insurance companies while the former do not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process these data, which, before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities are already forcing them to do so, although they have not received a fine for their negligence so far.
Some companies have also recently developed the results of laboratory tests and by linking them with drug consumption data they obtain more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those providing health services.
Already before Congress is the bill that gives the right to the authority for the control of companies specialized in the provision of personal data.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: therefore he developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, despite everything, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
