The European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutually trading partners, this issue in addition to the other largely global issues dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit that began yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President-in-Office, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission and Javier Solana, Chief Representative of Foreign Policy, welcomed Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, that is to increase their trade to more than one hundred billion euros.
In view of the fact that trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious objective.
In this way, the twenty-six existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have been legally harmonized, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among the Union's trading partners.
